// The `prelude.retry` sub-module: failure-recovery providers. Each is an ordinary `use` provider — its
// last parameter is the `continuation` the `use` form hands it (the rest of the enclosing block), and it
// RE-INVOKES that continuation to retry. Pure Katari over `prelude.time` (durable `sleep`) and the two
// error channels; no new reactor. The one-line integration is the provider:
//
//   use retry.exponential(initial_delay_milliseconds = 100.0, factor = 2.0, max_attempts = 5.0)
//   <the rest of the block — re-run on failure until it succeeds or the budget is spent>
//
// THE ONE NORMALIZATION BOUNDARY. Katari has two failure channels — a typed `throw[Error]` a program
// raises, and a `panic` the runtime raises — and a retry must treat both as "the attempt failed". `attempt`
// (below) is the SINGLE place both are caught and folded into one `outcome` sum, so every provider reasons
// about failure through one shape (`succeeded | failed`) and none re-implements the catch. A provider's
// only branching is `match` over that sum: there is no test on a counter anywhere.
//
// THE THROW PAYLOAD STAYS TYPED. The catch discharges `throw[Error]` for a generic @Error@ (inferred from
// the continuation's row), so a caught throw is reified as `thrown[Error]` — a caller keeps its typed error
// end to end, e.g. `use retry.exponential(...)` over an `http.fetch` still re-raises `throw[http.fetch_error]`,
// not an erased `throw[unknown]`.
//
// WHY EXHAUSTION RE-RAISES BY RUNNING THE LAST ATTEMPT UNCAUGHT. A caught `panic` cannot be re-raised from
// Katari (a program can never perform `panic`), so `exponential` cannot "hold the failure and re-raise it"
// when the budget is spent. Instead its FINAL attempt runs OUTSIDE `attempt` — a bare `continuation(...)` —
// so whatever it raises (throw or panic) propagates unchanged, the self-catch rule proxying it past this
// provider to the caller's handlers. This also removes any "is this the last attempt?" test: the `for` runs
// the catchable attempts and its `then` runs the final uncaught one — a structural split, not a branch on n.

@"The typed error a caught `throw` carried, reified so a provider can inspect it (`attended` describes it to
a human). @Error@ is the continuation's `throw` payload type, preserved end to end."
data thrown[Error](error: Error)

@"A caught runtime `panic`, reified with its @message@. Kept distinct from `thrown` because the two channels
mean different things — `thrown` is an anticipated typed error, `panicked` is a broken invariant — and a
handler may want to react to them differently."
data panicked(message: string)

// One attempt's failure, normalized across the two channels. (Type synonyms take no docs.)
type failure[Error] = thrown[Error] | panicked

@"An attempt that produced its value @value@."
data succeeded[R](value: R)

@"An attempt that failed, carrying its normalized @failure@."
data failed[Error](failure: failure[Error])

// The outcome of running the continuation once: a value, or a normalized failure. (Synonyms take no docs.)
type outcome[R, Error] = succeeded[R] | failed[Error]

@"Run @run@ once and reify its outcome: its value as `succeeded`, or a caught `throw` / `panic` as `failed`,
folding the two failure channels into one sum. This is the single boundary where a failure is caught — every
provider below composes retries out of it. @run@'s effect is the OVERWRITE row `{...E, throw[Error]}` (not the
union `E | throw[Error]`) precisely because this handler discharges the throw — the discord-provider shape;
@run@'s other effects @E@ flow through unchanged."
agent attempt[R, Error, effect E](
  run: agent (value: null) -> R with {...E, prelude.throw[Error]},
) -> outcome[R, Error] with E {
  use handler {
    // A caught panic and a caught throw both settle the attempt as `failed`; the panic clause is ambient
    // (addable to any handler, and its parameter is the wired-in `msg`) and the throw clause discharges
    // `throw[Error]` from `run`'s row.
    request panic(msg: string) { break failed[Error](failure = panicked(message = msg)) }
    request prelude.throw(error: Error) -> never { break failed[Error](failure = thrown(error = error)) }
  }
  succeeded(value = run(value = null))
}

@"Retry the rest of the block with exponential backoff, up to @max_attempts@ times. On failure number n
(1-based; a `throw` OR a `panic`) with n < @max_attempts@, durably sleep @initial_delay_milliseconds@ *
@factor@^(n-1) then re-run; on the @max_attempts@-th attempt the failure propagates UNCHANGED (that attempt
runs uncaught — a throw is re-thrown to the caller with its type, a panic re-panics). At least one attempt
always runs (a @max_attempts@ below 1 still runs once). Written `use retry.exponential(initial_delay_milliseconds
= ..., factor = ..., max_attempts = ...)`."
agent exponential[R, Error, effect E](
  initial_delay_milliseconds: number,
  factor: number,
  max_attempts: number,
  continuation: agent (value: null) -> R with {...E, prelude.throw[Error]},
) -> R with E | io | prelude.throw[Error] {
  // The catchable attempts: iterate `max_attempts - 1` times, threading the growing delay as state. A
  // success `break`s out with the value; a failure sleeps the current delay and continues to the next.
  for (let _attempt in array.range(start = 1, end = math.floor(value = max_attempts)), var delay = initial_delay_milliseconds) {
    match (attempt(run = continuation)) {
      case succeeded(value => value) -> { break value }
      case failed(failure => _failure) -> {
        time.sleep(milliseconds = delay)
        next with { delay = delay * factor }
      }
    }
  } then (_exhausted) {
    // Every catchable attempt failed: the final attempt runs uncaught, so its throw / panic re-raises
    // unchanged (the module header explains why this is how exhaustion re-raises).
    continuation(value = null)
  }
}

@"Retry the rest of the block FOREVER, with exponential backoff capped at @max_delay_milliseconds@. Every
failure (a `throw` OR a `panic`) is caught and retried, so this never re-raises and never returns on its
own — it is for daemons that must stay up across transient failures and restarts (e.g. keeping a
`time.watch` alive). The recursion IS the loop; its depth is the number of failures, not the number of
successes, so a healthy daemon accumulates nothing. Written `use retry.forever(initial_delay_milliseconds =
..., factor = ..., max_delay_milliseconds = ...)`."
agent forever[R, Error, effect E](
  initial_delay_milliseconds: number,
  factor: number,
  max_delay_milliseconds: number,
  continuation: agent (value: null) -> R with {...E, prelude.throw[Error]},
) -> R with E | io {
  match (attempt(run = continuation)) {
    case succeeded(value => value) -> value
    case failed(failure => _failure) -> {
      time.sleep(milliseconds = initial_delay_milliseconds)
      // `initial_delay_milliseconds` carries the CURRENT delay, so each retry grows it by @factor@ up to
      // the cap. Recursing (rather than looping) keeps every retry a fresh durable delegation that recovers
      // cleanly across a restart.
      forever(
        initial_delay_milliseconds = math.min(left = initial_delay_milliseconds * factor, right = max_delay_milliseconds),
        factor = factor,
        max_delay_milliseconds = max_delay_milliseconds,
        continuation = continuation,
      )
    }
  }
}

@"Raised by `attended` on each failure, carrying the normalized @failure@ (typed error preserved) so whoever
answers can see what went wrong. Unhandled, it escalates to a durable open question that parks the run until
`katari answer`; an application may install its own `attention` handler to intercept it (e.g. post to Discord
and wait there), then `next null` to trigger the retry (or `break` to give up with a value)."
request attention[Error](failure: failure[Error]) -> null

@"Retry the rest of the block with a human in the loop: on failure (a `throw` OR a `panic`) perform
`attention` carrying the normalized failure, and when it resolves (the human re-authorized, fixed the
config, ...) re-run the block. Unhandled, `attention` escalates to a durable open question the run parks on;
an application can intercept it with its own handler. This is the re-auth story — a revoked token throws,
`attended` turns it into a notification, the user re-authorizes and answers, and the block re-executes.
Written `use retry.attended()`."
agent attended[R, Error, effect E](
  continuation: agent (value: null) -> R with {...E, prelude.throw[Error]},
) -> R with E | attention[Error] {
  match (attempt(run = continuation)) {
    case succeeded(value => value) -> value
    case failed(failure => detail) -> {
      attention(failure = detail)
      attended(continuation = continuation)
    }
  }
}
